JOHANNESBURG &#8211; South Africa&#8217;s rand weakened early on Friday as the dollar firmed after upbeat US private sector job figures appeared to boost the prospects for US interest rate hike this month.At 0645 GMT, the rand traded at 12.9400 per dollar, 0.54% weaker than its overnight close, giving up gains made in the previous session.The rand firmed on Thursday after ratings agency Fitch affirmed the country&#8217;s sub-investment grade rating with a stable outlook.S&amp;P Global Ratings, which cut South Africa&#8217;s foreign debt rating to &#8220;junk&#8221; status in April, is expected to announce an update today.Focus also on closely-watched US non-farm payrolls report out later day.Stocks were set to open higher at 0700 GMT, with the JSE securities exchange&#8217;s Top-40 futures index up 0.45%.In fixed income, the yield for the benchmark government bond due in 2026 was down 2 basis points to 8.525%.